The Chamber of the Adepts and the Adyton

The Chamber of the Adepts is a long-standing icon within the Western Mystery tradition. Its origins are found within the Golden Dawn through the Rosicrucians. There is an abundance of information to be found on it, and I will leave this up to the individual Adept to discover. One of the clearest instructions within the Holy Books of MA concerns this chamber, and its uses. Whether one calls it the Chamber of the Adepts, the Adyton of the Seven, or the Sevenfold Cloister, it all means the same. 

It is a place of meditation and ritual whose design relates to the deeper mysteries of Ma through its sacred geometry and mathematical synchronicity. Thus, the Chamber of the Adepts now is retitled and reinterpreted as the Adyton of the Seven, which will serve as the Sevenfold Cloister of the Order of the Argentum Aurora. 

The Adyton of the Seven is a reinterpretation of the Adept Chamber in terms of the Aeon of MA. There is much within our writings concerning this most celebrated idea. The use of the word Adyton itself is curious, as it means the innermost sanctuary of the temple, a place that only the priest could enter, and from which their oracles were received. This word is synonymous with “the Holy of Holies” or “the Inner Sanctum”. Within the structure of the Greek temples, the Adyton was a room within the Temple proper (ναός), whose access was restricted. This holds an interesting history, for in the Ptolemaic period of Egypt, the Adyton referred to that which was hidden inside the Inner Sanctum of the Temples, existing in a darkness meant to represent the primordial darkness before creation. Archaeologists extended it to refer to the central room of pyramids. Around this room was often a Labyrinth of tunnels and paths meant to detour those who would rob and desecrate the tombs of those buried within. 

In Greek, the word Adyton is ΑΔΥΤΟΝ, equaling 825\. The idea that the Adyton is concealed within the Temple is shown by the reversal of 825 which is 577, meaning, in Hebrew, “the Concealed of the Concealed”.  577 is also the sum of the first 3 words of the MAAT notariqon, meaning “Sanctuary of the Hidden Goddess”.

*The Cubit of AMUN*

In this way, all 80 parts of the tesseract are perfectly aligned with all 80 possible tetragrams, with no duplicates, and no missing numbers.

Epilogue

In the traditional tarot, the Major Arcana contains a cast of characters in a highly symbolic tableau. In this procession, only two cards are objects: the Chariot and the Tower. In the former, a hidden figure sits and holds the Grail. In the latter, human figures are seen falling from the parapets as the Tower explodes. This card has been given more different names than any other card: Sagitta (Arrow); la Casa del Diavolo (House of the Devil); Fulmine (Lightning); Fuoco (Fire); la Casa del Danato (House of the Damned); Inferno (Hell); la Casa di Plutone (House of Pluto); la Foudre (Lightning) and la Maison Dieu (the House of God, or ‘God House’).

The last of these names was used in the Tarot de Marseilles, which heavily influenced the Golden Dawn, and in turn the work of Crowley. While all the other names in Italian refer to fiery things, hell, the underworld etc., and the idea of lightning even carries over into one of the early French decks, this last term is the most curious, and yet the most fitting for our purpose.   The French term is usually translated as the House of God, but since grammar rules were not fixed in those early days, the name can also be God House. And this term has a specific meaning in medieval France. A ‘God House’ was a place of refuge, a hospital for poor pilgrims, a place of sanctuary and comfort. It might even refer to a Church, a place to encounter the Divine Spirit. 

It is precisely this function of the God House that is the purpose of the Adyton. While it most certainly can be the home of fire and lightning, these forces are emanated *from within* the Tower, not struck by it from above. And the reason these forces do so is because the Adept is within the Tower, taking refuge from the world, and communing with their Angel. The Tower is therefore the Temple, and in this essay that Temple has been described in the utmost detail. The components of the Temple are both simple and complex: 4 Pillars of the elements and the Sphinxes; a Cubical Altar that is in 4 dimensions; and a 4-sided polyhedron, sliced off to make a seat for the Adept, surrounded by the 7 walls, and the heptagonal floor with its letters of power, and the heptagonal ceiling with its heptagram of enlightenment. For Lightning is one of the most appropriate of names for the Tower, in respect of the fact that the Tower is a 7-sided prism, designed to refract and convey the messages of the Star Goddess.

Whether it is called the Adyton of the 7, the Vault of the Adepts, the Well of the Seven, or the Bastion, it is still the same building with the same purpose: a fortress of refuge for weary wanderers, and a place where the science of Trigrammaton mixes with the Art of the Aeon.

The Tower is a recurring theme in the Holy Books of M.I.X., and many of the details of its construction and purpose can be found in these scriptures. All of these details of the Tower have been worked out thoroughly in this outstanding compilation. Frater M.G. has collated an immense amount of data to form the basis of the science of the Adyton. And what the Adept does within this space is the Art of our gnosis. May this essay serve the Adept well, in their journey of discovery through the labyrinth of time, and the sweet mastery of the Space of MA.

I thoroughly endorse this essay, and consider it the equivalent of the required thesis of a Magister Templi 8⊗3, the Grade which Frater M.G. has attained, and which he has duly earned by his unflagging devotion to the Work.
